# React conventions
- Use functional components and hooks.
- Prefer small components; extract reusable logic into custom hooks.
- Do not duplicate state across multiple components; derive state when possible.

# TypeScript & API contracts
- All API payloads must be typed (no `any` / untyped JSON).
- Keep API DTOs in dedicated modules and reuse them across components.

# Tailwind conventions
- Use Tailwind utility classes for styling via `className`.
- Avoid inline styles unless strictly required.
- For long conditional class lists, use a helper like `clsx` (or equivalent) instead of manual string concatenation.
- Keep UI colors low-saturation: prefer neutral/grayscale (e.g., `slate`, `stone`, `gray`) and muted tones; avoid highly saturated/vivid brand colors unless required for a clear affordance.

# Accessibility & UX
- Ensure interactive elements have accessible labels (`aria-label`, `role`, or visible text).
- Handle loading and error states explicitly for async operations.

# Frontend security notes
- Do not trust client input: treat all user-provided data as untrusted (validate on the backend as the source of truth).
- Prevent XSS: never render untrusted HTML; avoid `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` and escape/encode any text coming from search/snippets.
- Do not store secrets/tokens in insecure locations (prefer `httpOnly` cookies for auth tokens when possible).

